</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22ECEFC4DFAED" blockId="5.[174,1233,895,1850]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
S t r a t i g r a p h i c a l r a n g e. Late Miocene — early Pliocene of Mill-Langenboom, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC668FF2EAEFEB2FB0E" box="[174,373,1247,1273]" name="Netherlands" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">The Netherlands</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D174FFC669D72EAEFDBDFB0D" author="Wijnker, E. &amp; Bor, T. J. &amp; Wesselingh, F. P." box="[390,634,1247,1274]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" pagination="165 - 180" refId="ref10789" refString="Wijnker, E., Bor, T. J., Wesselingh, F. P. et al. Neogene stratigraphy of the Langenboom locality (Noord-Brabant, The Netherlands) // Netherlands J. Geosciences. - 2008. - 87. - P. 165 - 180." type="book chapter" year="2008">Wijnker et al., 2008</bibRefCitation>
) and late Miocene (early–middle Tortonian, 8.0– 11.5 ma) of Gram, Jutland, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC669BE2E8EFD98FAEE" box="[495,607,1279,1305]" name="Denmark" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Denmark</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D174FFC66A3F2E8EFCBAFAED" author="Hansen, J. &amp; Hansen, T." box="[622,893,1279,1306]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" pagination="157 - 169" refId="ref8863" refString="Hansen, J., Hansen, T. Stratigraphy and sea-level fluctuations in the Upper Miocene Gram Formation, southwestern Denmark // Bulletin of the Geological Society of Denmark. - 2003. - 50. - P. 157 - 169." type="book chapter" year="2003">Hansen, Hansen, 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C363652AD174FFC668B22F51FC6EFAAD" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22F51FC6EFAAD" blockId="5.[174,1233,895,1850]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">E t y m o l o g y. After n o r d (Danish: noun, neuter) = the North, Latinized to n o r d i c a (adj.) = from the North, referring to the northern part of Europe.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C363652AD174FFC668B22F11FEA7FA2E" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22F11FEA7FA2E" blockId="5.[174,1233,895,1850]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">D i a g n o s i s. Deltoid crest of humerus with ventral border very sharp and sculptured, overhanging deep spiral groove; lesser tubercle flattened, rectangular, deviates almost 45° from bone’s axis; head compressed in cranio-caudal direction; ratio of head width / head height — 97 %.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C363652AD174FFC468B22F91FDBEFE7E" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="426" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22F91FE10F90D" blockId="5.[174,1233,895,1850]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d c o m p a r i s o n. Postcranial elements of 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66BA72FAEFB17FA0E" authorityName="Koretsky, Rahmat et Peters" authorityYear="2014" box="[1014,1232,1503,1529]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nordica">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66BA72FAEFB17FA0E" box="[1014,1232,1503,1529]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Gryphoca nordica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belong to a medium-sized representative of 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66AB62F8EFC9FF9EE" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1866" box="[743,856,1535,1561]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="430" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phocinae">Phocinae</taxonomicName>
, equivalent in size to Recent 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC668FF2C6EFE68F9CE" box="[174,431,1567,1593]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC668FF2C6EFE6CF9CE" baseAuthorityName="Zimmermann" baseAuthorityYear="1783" box="[174,427,1567,1593]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Histriophoca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciata">Histriophoca fasciata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Morphological characters similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66B302C6EFBE2F9CE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[865,1061,1567,1593]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66B302C6EFBE2F9CE" box="[865,1061,1567,1593]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Gryphoca similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(pl. 2, 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66C232C6EFB01F9CE" box="[1138,1222,1567,1593]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">2A–2D</emphasis>
) are: the deltoid crest is strongly developed, with its maximum width in its proximal part at the level of the lesser tubercle. The deltoid tuberosity is weakly developed, but clearly seen on the proximal part of the deltoid crest. The intertubercular groove is narrow and deep. The ventral border of the deltoid crest is very sharp and sculptured, overhanging as an anconeal crest (ac, pl. 2, 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC669AE2CCEFDE5F92E" box="[511,546,1727,1753]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">1D</emphasis>
). The radial groove (= musculospiral groove) is strongly developed (sg, pl. 2, 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC669F32CAEFE02F90E" box="[418,453,1759,1785]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">1D</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC468B22C8EFED3FEDE" blockId="5.[174,1233,895,1850]" lastBlockId="7.[174,1233,175,1193]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="426" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
The new species 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC669F02D71FDDDF8EE" authorityName="Koretsky, Rahmat et Peters" authorityYear="2014" box="[417,538,1791,1818]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nordica">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC669F02D71FDDDF8EE" box="[417,538,1791,1818]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">G. nordica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66AFC2C8EFCAAF8EE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[685,877,1791,1817]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66AFC2C8EFCAAF8EE" box="[685,877,1791,1817]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Gryphoca similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its smaller size. In addition, the head of the humerus is compressed in the cranio-caudal direction, not round in shape. The proximal part of the deltoid crest is located at the same level as the lesser tubercle and slightly above the head. The lesser tubercle resembles a flattened rectangle, deviates almost 45° from the bone’s axis, and is situated slightly above the head, but higher than the greater tubercle.
</paragraph>
