<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B22B5EFDBEFE7E" blockId="7.[174,1233,175,1193]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">The supracondylar fossa of the femur, located above the lateral condyle, is easily visible. The patellar surface is very pronounced, sharp and has a prominent outlinesculptural compared to the bone’s overall surface.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C363652AD176FFC468B22BE1FEFDFB5E" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B22BE1FC8FFD7D" blockId="7.[174,1233,175,1193]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
D i s c u s s i o n. The rare genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC46A182BFEFD7EFE5E" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[585,697,399,425]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46A182BFEFD7EFE5E" box="[585,697,399,425]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was introduced by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC46BC82BE1FB4FFE5D" author="Van Beneden, P. J." box="[921,1160,399,426]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref10746" refString="Van Beneden, P. J. Description des ossements fossiles des environs d'Anvers, 1. Pinnipedes ou amphitheriens // Musee Royal d'Histoire Naturelle de Belgique, Annales. - 1877. - 1. - P. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1877">Van Beneden (1877)</bibRefCitation>
based on material from the Antwerp area, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46A082BDEFD78FE3E" box="[601,703,431,457]" name="Belgium" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Belgium</collectingCountry>
. Although the genus is known to researchers by name, it appears that no one except 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC46AD72BA1FCC0FE1D" author="Ray, C. E." box="[646,775,463,490]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref10216" refString="Ray, C. E. Phoca wymani and other Tertiary seals (Mammalia: Phocidae) described from the eastern seaboard of North America // Smithsonian Contributions to Paleobiology. - 1976. - 28. - P. 1 - 36." type="book chapter" year="1976">Ray (1976)</bibRefCitation>
has re-examined the original material critically. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC469732B9EFD8FFDFD" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Ray, C. E." box="[290,584,495,522]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="81 - 140" refId="ref9574" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Ray, C. E. Phocidae of the Pliocene of eastern USA // Geology and paleontology of the Lee Creek Mine, North Carolina IV / Eds C. E. Ray, D. A. Bohaska, I. A. Koretsky et al. - Virginia Museum of Natural History, 2008. - 15 (Special Publication). - P. 81 - 140." type="book chapter" year="2008">Koretsky and Ray (2008)</bibRefCitation>
re-evaluated, described and compared West European and North American material, and proposed a diagnosis for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC46C53287EFBB5FDDE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[1026,1138,527,553]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46C53287EFBB5FDDE" box="[1026,1138,527,553]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In this study, we assign a new, smaller species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC46AD92841FCC4FDBE" authorityName="Koretsky &amp; Rahmat &amp; Peters" authorityYear="2014" box="[648,771,559,586]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nordica">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46AD92841FD5BFDBD" box="[648,668,560,586]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46AFB285EFCC4FDBE" box="[682,771,559,585]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">nordica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC46BFA285EFBDCFDBE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[939,1051,559,585]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46BFA285EFBDCFDBE" box="[939,1051,559,585]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of only a few fragmentary and rolled bones (but with very distinctive morphological features) from the late Miocene of Northern and Western Europe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B228E1FEDBFCFE" blockId="7.[174,1233,175,1193]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
<location id="8EA6607AD176FFC468B228E1FE86FD5D" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03D087B7D174FFC468FF293EFEFDFB5E:8EA6607AD176FFC468B228E1FE86FD5D" box="[227,321,656,682]" country="Denmark" name="Because" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Because</location>
none of the specimens in the 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46AEF28FEFCE9FD5E" box="[702,814,655,681]" name="Denmark" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Denmark</collectingCountry>
collection is complete, we choose the humerus from The Netherlands (with the same geological age, better preservation, and apparently the same morphology; see pl. 2, 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46ABD28BEFCF8FD1E" box="[748,831,719,745]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">2A–2D</emphasis>
, and table 2) as the best available 
<typeStatus id="54C28803D176FFC468FF289EFEDFFCFE" box="[174,280,751,777]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B2297EFD05FC1E" blockId="7.[174,1233,175,1193]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
The fragmentary remains, as well as the lack of further postcranial elements, may raise some doubts about their assignment to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC46B6B295EFC6DFCBE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[826,938,815,841]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46B6B295EFC6DFCBE" box="[826,938,815,841]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the preserved material (four humeri and a femur) and previous publications based on the Western European and eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC469E6291EFD92FC7E" box="[439,597,879,905]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">United States</collectingCountry>
material (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC46A9D291EFCBAFC7E" author="Van Beneden, P. J." box="[716,893,879,905]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref10746" refString="Van Beneden, P. J. Description des ossements fossiles des environs d'Anvers, 1. Pinnipedes ou amphitheriens // Musee Royal d'Histoire Naturelle de Belgique, Annales. - 1877. - 1. - P. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1877">Beneden, 1877</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC46BD9291EFBB0FC7D" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Ray, C. E." box="[904,1143,879,906]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="81 - 140" refId="ref9574" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Ray, C. E. Phocidae of the Pliocene of eastern USA // Geology and paleontology of the Lee Creek Mine, North Carolina IV / Eds C. E. Ray, D. A. Bohaska, I. A. Koretsky et al. - Virginia Museum of Natural History, 2008. - 15 (Special Publication). - P. 81 - 140." type="book chapter" year="2008">Koretsky, Ray, 2008</bibRefCitation>
), allow, with a high degree of probability, assignment of this seal to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC46BAD29FEFBABFC5E" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[1020,1132,911,937]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC46BAD29FEFBABFC5E" box="[1020,1132,911,937]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the introduction of a new taxon of specific rank. We think this approach is more justified than establishment of a new taxon of generic rank.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B2299EFEFDFB5E" blockId="7.[174,1233,175,1193]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
Furthermore, according to the ecomorphotype hypothesis of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC46B95299EFB42FBFD" author="Koretsky, I. A." box="[964,1157,1007,1034]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" refId="ref9287" refString="Koretsky, I. A. Morphology and systematics of Miocene Phocinae (Mammalia: Carnivora) from Paratethys and the North Atlantic Region // Geologica Hungarica. Ser. Paleontol. - 2001. - 54. - 109 p." type="book" year="2001">Koretsky (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, these bones belong to the same group (ecomorphotype V) on the basis of characters such as: lesser tubercle slightly higher than or at same level as the head of the humerus, and deviates from the bone’s axis; intertubercular groove narrow; maximum width of the deltoid crest located in its proximal part. Ecomorphological analysis is here applied on the level of alpha systematics.
</paragraph>
